title: Fix bug in handling the call stack.
message:
Fix bug in handling the call stack.

Documentation in Appendix D (D-2) of the personnal programming manual
says that past the 6th call the return address is not recorded but the
call is done and it is not an error.

The following program when run must return 191 (tested on real TI-59).

   A + 1 = r/s
   lbl A B + 2 inv sbr
   lbl B C + 4 inv sbr
   lbl C D + 8 inv sbr
   lbl D E + 16 inv sbr
   lbl E A' + 32 inv sbr
   lbl A' B' + 64 = inv sbr
   lbl B + 128 = inv sbr

That is, for the seventh call (B') the return address is not recorded,
so the very last inv sbr returns to the instruction after A' which is
the sixth call. So we do not add the number 64.

title: When a transfer fails the PC must be on the actual address.
message:
When a transfer fails the PC must be on the actual address.

   LRN
   GTO Lnx
   R/S

Runnig the program:

   RST R/S

We must be on instruction 001:

   LRN
   001 23

title: A Prt instruction ends a number.
message:
A Prt instruction ends a number.

   1
   Prt
   2
   Sto 01

   Then memory 01 must contain 2.

This was working in interactive mode but not in program.

title: Rework the TRACE mode.
message:
Rework the TRACE mode.

The trace mode is used to print instructions and numbers on the printer.
The trace mode is not anymore triggered by the flg-9 but by the special
operation 98. This is needed as the trace mode is not reset by RST for
example, but RST does reset the flags. Anyway, better to use the op 98
as the trace mode is activated by pressing the TRACE button of the PC-100.

This first implementation is maybe not perfect and maybe not exactly
what was printed by the original PC-100, but far better than just
printing the numbers as done before.

title: New Number class implementation using 13bits BCD.
message:
New Number class implementation using 13bits BCD.

This version is lot closer to original TI and ensure proper calculation
without rounding error. All code messing with rounding is removed.

Note that all tests are passing.

Doing 100 times : +0.05 +0.1 -0.05 and then one time -10 now really
report the original number. This was not the case with the double
(binary based) number which has inherent precision loss.

title: Move code to new Number API.
message:
Move code to new Number API.

This version should never be used. It is a code refactoring. All
numbers (X, T, memories, stack) are using the new Number class.

title: Initial version of Number.java.
message:
Initial version of Number.java.

This class is to be used for all numbers handled in the emulator. For now
the implementation is based on double. So this is the same as currently
used in the emulator. Some code to mess with rounding has been removed
and so the calculator won't report proper result in some case.

The TI-59 emulator should never be built with this implementation. It is
a first step (code refactoring) toward a better number support based on
13bits BCD numbers.

Note that some tests have been added, to run:

   ant signed
   make -C tests

The current version do not pass all tests.

title: Fix GTO Ind implementation.
message:
Fix GTO Ind implementation.

After a GTO Ind we expect a single byte which is the register number.
The following program must display 1 when pressing A.

   1
   r/s

   lbl A
   0.9 sto 01
   gto ind 01

Tested on a real TI-59.

title: Fix OP ind semantics.
message:
Fix OP ind semantics.

First if the value pointed is negative do nothing.

Second do not round the indirect value but truncate it. The following
program has been tested on a real TI-59 and the display must be 2:

   0 sto 00

   20.1 sto 01
   op* 01            ; ok incr R00
   20.9 sto 01
   op* 01            ; ok incr R00
   20.9 +/- sto 01
   op* 21            ; does nothing

   rcl 00
   r/s

message:
New implementation of AbsIntPart for better precision.

Fix MU-08 for example.

title: Indirect reference to memory must use the int part (not rounded).
message:
Indirect reference to memory must use the int part (not rounded).

   0 sto 14
   14.1 sto 00
   1 sm* 00
   14.5 sto 00
   1 sm* 00
   14.9 sto 00
   1 sm* 00
   rcl 14
   r/s

This program must display 3. Verified on real TI-59.

title: As for a real TI-59 restrict the parentheses.
message:
As for a real TI-59 restrict the parentheses.

The following program has been tested on a real TI-59.

   1 0 sto 0
   (          ; 004
   inv stf 7  ; clear flag 7
   op 30      ; decrement R0
   op 18      ; set flag 7 if no error
   iff 7 004
   ce
   rcl 0
   r/s

Entering : CLR ( ( RST R/S must display 2
           CLR RST R/S     must display 0

title: Add support for labels in assembler.
message: Add support for labels in assembler.

title: Keep inv state across label/Nop.
message:
Keep inv state across label/Nop.

   lbl A              lbl A
   inv                inv
                      Nop
   lbl B              Nop
   stf 0              stf 0
   iff 0 C            iff 0 C
   9                  9
   r/s                r/s

   lbl C              lbl C
   1                  1
   r/s                r/s

Pressing A should display 9 and B (on first program only) 1.

This has been tested on a real TI-59.

title: After a branch if we have a number it must replace X.
message:
After a branch if we have a number it must replace X.

This is a continuation of previous patch but for the flag-branching.
Note also that this was already the behavior for an rcl where we
land after a branch. So the only effect of this patch is to avoid
accumulating digits after a branch.

The following program has been tested on a real TI-59:

    cms               4
    2                 sto 5
    iff 0 D           1 + 2
    5 sum 8           iff 0 E
    rcl 8             rcl 5
    r/s               =
                      r/s

The display must be 5.

title: Fix D.MS semantic to match real TI-59.
message:
Fix D.MS semantic to match real TI-59.

The D.MS must be done on the displayed value if a Fix-nn is set
and not on the actual number.

265.28    265.28
fix 1     265.3
fix 9     265.28
fix 1     265.3
dms       265.5
inv fix   265.5
inv dms   265.3

Tested on a real TI-59.

title: Fix handling of negative numbers passed through sqrt/x2.
message:
Fix handling of negative numbers passed through sqrt/x2.

The following program:

   2          2
   +/-        +/-
   √x         √x
   x²         rtn
   prt
   adv
   rtn
   ------------------
   2          1.41...    display flashing , program must stop at rtn.

Interactively, 2 +/1 √x display 1.41... flashing, then x² display 2
flashing. The emulator won't accept x² interactively, a CLR is needed
to continue using the calculator. This does not seem a bad restriction.

Tested on a real TI-59.

0           0           1           0

+           x=t E       x=t E       +

title: Fix handling of transfer to location (goto, x=t...).
message:
Fix handling of transfer to location (goto, x=t...).

The branch may be invalid (an undefined label or a wrong numeric
address 999 for example) and the application should be in error
state only if the branch is to be taken. This has been tested
in a real TI-59.

For example:

0          0            stflg 01      1
x<>t       x<>t         ifflg 01 E    sto 01
1          1            8             dsz 01 E
x=t E      x=t 999      r/s           8
8          8                          r/s
r/s        r/s

Should all display 8.

But:

1          1          0             inv stflg 01    2
x<>t       x<>t       x<>t          ifflg 01 E      sto 01
1          1          1             8               dsz 01 E
x=t E      x=t 999    inv x=t E     r/s             8
8          8          8                             r/s
r/s        r/s        r/s

Should all set the calculator in error state with a flashing
1 (2 for dsz test) number.

title: Emulate the HIR 05-08 register as printer register.
message:
Emulate the HIR 05-08 register as printer register.

In the original TI-59 the HIR 05-08 register (i.e. the stack registers) are

by ensuring that the stack registers are updated accordingly.

title: Implement HIR support.
message:
Implement HIR support.

The HIR instruction are officially undocumented but are well known and
described and used in many programs. The HIR instructions are just dealing
with the 8 stack internal registers.

The operations are:

   HIR CN : 82 CN

Where N is in range 0 .. 7 and correspond to the 8 internal registers with
0 being the currently displayed value (X).

And C is:
  0  : STO : X         -> Stack (N)
  1  : RCL : Stack (N) -> X
  3  : ADD : Stack (N) += X
  4  : MUL : Stack (N) *= X
  5  : SUB : Stack (N) -= X
  6  : DIV : Stack (N) /= X

title: Adjust the pause instruction to correspond better to real TI-59.
message:
Adjust the pause instruction to correspond better to real TI-59.

I did some timing and a real TI-59 is counting up to 51 in 30 seconds
with the following simple program:

   + 1 = <pause> RST

The Android application was counting up to 127 in the same time. This
little delay adjustement will make the application closer to what a
real TI-59 is doing.
